living in refuge services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that do not count as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exempt accommodation may be affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by the spare room subsidy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if temporarily staying in self-contained accommodation that may be considered to be too large for their family size. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This may happen in a minori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty of cases where a refuge service may have to use self-contained accommodation to support a woman where a shared house is not suitable, such as where the woman has complex needs/disability, or has a child with behavioural difficulties, or if a shared hous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e has an age bar on older male children, and the survivor has older</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> male children over that age (for example,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 14 or 15 year olds); or because there is nowhere safe to move on to.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may apply to survivors living in their own homes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have high housing costs such as if they have fled the home and been provided w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ith temporary accommodation (which can be expensive particularly if the woman has children and so needs more than one bedroom) or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if living in high rent areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The cap may also apply to residents staying in a refuge service (though if the refuge service counts as exempt accommodation the refuge rent can be disregarded in the calculation of the cap). Where the service does not meet the exempt accommodation a survi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vor could be capped if the combination of their family entitlement and the refuge rent takes them above the limit for the cap. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of particular concern to Women’s Aid is the situation of a survivor who has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">left their home because of violence or the threat o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f violence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to live in a refuge service (or other temporary accommodation). In such situations they can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">receive housing benefit on both the refuge service and their original </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for up to a year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if they intend to return there. If a refuge is not counted as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exempt accommodation, any survivor with dual rent liability and dual housing benefit would inevitably be capped. This would make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nonse